    {
      "id": "general-science-chemistry-food-preservation-nutrition-medicine-q8",
      "type": "single-choice",
      "text": "Aspartame is an artificial sweetner sold in the market. It consists of amino acids and provides calories like other amino acids. Yet, it is used as a low calorie sweetening agent in food items. What is the basis of this use?",
      "options": [
        {
          "id": "a",
          "text": "Aspartame is as sweet as table sugar, but unlike table sugar, it is not readily oxidized in the human body due to lack of requisite enzymes"
        },
        {
          "id": "b",
          "text": "When aspartame is used in food processing, the sweet taste remains, but it becomes resistant to oxidation"
        },
        {
          "id": "c",
          "text": "Aspartame is as sweet as sugar but after ingestion into the body, it is converted into metabolites that yield no calories"
        },
        {
          "id": "d",
          "text": "Aspartame is several times sweeter than table sugar, hence food items made with small quantities of aspartame yield fewer calories on oxidation"
        }
      ],
      "correctOptionIds": [
        "d"
      ],
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "marks": 1,
      "explanation": "The correct answer is option D: Aspartame is several times sweeter than table sugar, hence food items made with small quantities of aspartame yield fewer calories on oxidation",
      "estimatedTimeSeconds": 110,
      "tags": [
        "IAS (Pre) 2011",
        "chemistry"
      ]
